******
[1] USA (Rhode Island)
Date: Thu 2 Oct 2014
Source: Fox 17 News, CNN report [summ., edited]
http://fox17online.com/2014/10/02/enterovirus-d68-found-in-4-patients-who-have-died-including-10-year-old-girl/


Samples collected from 4 patients who recently died have tested positive for enterovirus D68, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. It is unclear what role the virus played in their deaths. In fact, it's possible that enterovirus had nothing to do with them. The virus is very common, especially in the late summer and early fall, with the CDC estimating 10 million to 15 million infections each year in the United States.

Yet the deaths do raise an alarm because this year [2014] has been worse than some other years, since enterovirus D68 has been sending more children than usual to the hospital with severe respiratory illnesses. It seems to be most affecting children with a history of asthma or breathing problems.

As of Wednesday [1 Oct 2014] the CDC had confirmed 500 people in 42 states have respiratory illnesses caused by enterovirus D68. Those infected include a 10-year-old from Cumberland [Providence County], Rhode Island. She died [22 Sep 2014] at a Hasbro Children's Hospital, according to her obituary, though it wasn't until Wednesday that the state Health Department announced that she'd tested positive for enterovirus D68. Dr. Michael Fine, Rhode Island's Department of Health director, told reporters Wednesday that the girl "died from overwhelming _Staphylococcus aureus_ sepsis." _Staphylococcus aureus_ is a bacterium resistant to many antibiotics, while sepsis is an illness affecting all parts of the body that springs up in response to an infection, according to the CDC.

That determination notwithstanding, Fine also noted that "cultures also showed the presence of enterovirus D68." He explained that the child, who was otherwise healthy, experienced shortness of breath "and really by the time she got to the hospital, everything fell apart very quickly within 24 hours." Fine added that "it's not clear what role the enterovirus had, but clearly (this) was a sepsis death. We don't know which came 1st [referring to enterovirus and sepsis], and that's not possible to know with the current state of our science."

Enterovirus may also be linked to a small number of cases of a mysterious neurologic illness seen in Colorado, Boston [Massachusetts] and Michigan. Doctors in Colorado spotted it 1st -- a group of 10 children hospitalized with limb weakness, cranial nerve dysfunction and abnormalities in their spinal gray matter. Doctors at Boston Children's Hospital have since identified 4 patients with the same symptoms. And a child in Washtenaw County, Michigan, also developed partial paralysis in the lower limbs after being hospitalized with the virus, the Michigan Department of Community Health said Wednesday [1 Oct 2014].

